description:
Corporate espionage meets science fiction. What would you do when corporations start buying up planets, star systems, entire galaxies?

Prometheus, Inc.: for hundreds of years, they’ve served as a shining example of how corporations can bring peace and prosperity to even the farthest reaches of the galaxy. But it’s all been a front. They’ve been amassing power and resources, biding their time to take over. And the time is now.Torchbearer is a science fiction epic that combines corporate espionage with science fiction and focuses on the individuals inside the resistance movement The Torchbearers and the actions they take to stop Prometheus before it’s too late.

Get it digitally from http://www.torchbearercomic.com
name: Torchbearer

Numbering continues in Happy Rabbit (Standard, 1951 series).

Like its sister publications Barnyard Comics and Coo Coo Comics, Happy Comics was an comedy title aimed at younger readers. The most notable character was Happy Rabbit, a somewhat accident-prone bunny. Happy had a girlfriend, the hard-to-please Bonny Bunny, as well as an inventor uncle who could be counted on to provide him with an array of unworkable devices. Other characters featured in this series included Wally Wolf and Dizzy Duck.
name: Happy Comics

deck: Standard, 1944 Series Published in English (United States)
description:
Published from 1944 to October 1947 with 11 total issues numbered 1-11.

A 1940's title from William Wise/Visual Editions, offered wholesome and generally accurate pictorial biographies of famous figures from history. Each issue featured four to six literate, well-illustrated stories about characters from all walks of life.Characters ranged from industrialists like Henry Ford to pirates like Captain Kidd to explorers, adventurers, and scientists. William Wise took its educational mission seriously and strove for factual accuracy and entertainment in equal measure, to inspire children to strive for greatness in their own lives.
name: It Really Happened
